In [10]:
# Map the conference, division, and championship data from cell above
# to new columns in the dataset

def get_teamInfo(row, category):
    '''Function to map conference and division info'''
    obj = list(filter(lambda x: x['name'] == row['TEAM'], team_info))[0]
    return obj[category]

def is_champion(row):
    '''Function to map yearly league champion info'''
    if champions[row['year']] == row['TEAM']:
        return 1
    
df1['conference'] = df1.apply(lambda x: get_teamInfo(x, 'conf'), axis=1)
df1['division'] = df1.apply(lambda x: get_teamInfo(x, 'div'), axis=1)
df1['champion'] = df1.apply(is_champion, axis=1)

Plot the heatmap (extra step to highlight yearly champions)¶

In [21]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(14,10))

# plot the heatmap with data from pivoted Win% dataframe
# include Win count dataframe for the annotations
# this will plot the heatmap based on win% but show the win count as it's easier to read
# (TODO: normalize years with under 82 games using win% so win counts aren't skewed)
ax = sns.heatmap(data=df2, cmap="YlGnBu", annot=a)

# Create a third pivoted dataframe using 'champions' to highlight champs in heatmap
b = df1[['year','TEAM','champion']]
b = b.groupby(['TEAM','year']).sum().unstack()
b.columns = b.columns.droplevel()

# Set empty array to store indices of champs
champ_indices = []
# Loop through each row and then value of the pivoted champions dataframe
# storing the indices in order to highlight them
for i, row in enumerate(b.values):
    for j, val in enumerate(row):
        if val == 1:
            champ_indices.append((j,i))
            
# Loop through indices and apply red border to each one
for coords in champ_indices:
    ax.add_patch(Rectangle(coords,1,1, edgecolor='red'))

ax.set_title('Win% By Year\n(with win totals)')

plt.show()

Observations¶

  • Spurs have been good the most consistently over this time period
  • Outside of the Spurs, it's hard to stay really good for more than a few years in a row
  • Some of the worst stretches in this time period:
    • Bulls after Jordan left
    • Grizzlies and Warriors through 2003
    • T-Wolves after KG left
    • Kings after Bibby left
    • Wizards 2008-2014
    • Lakers after Kobe got hurt
    • 76ers 2013-2017

3) Further exploration¶

Create a correlation matrix and plot to check which stats are highly correlated¶

In [25]:
# Correlation Matrix
corr_matrix = df1[['WIN%', 'MIN', 'PTS',
       'FGM', 'FGA', 'FG%', '3PM', '3PA', '3P%', 'FTM', 'FTA', 'FT%', 'OREB',
       'DREB', 'REB', 'AST', 'TOV', 'STL', 'BLK', 'BLKA', 'PF', 'PFD', '+/-']].corr()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,10))
dropSelf = np.zeros_like(corr_matrix)
dropSelf[np.triu_indices_from(dropSelf)] = True
sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, vmin=-1, cmap='coolwarm', linewidths=.5, square=True,
                annot=True, fmt=".1f", mask=dropSelf)
plt.show()

Observations:¶

  • The highest correlation (other than +/- which is obvious) for Win% out of these basic team stats is FG%. This makes intuitive sense since missing fewest shots possible is advantageous, but it is interesting that it is a better predictor than PTS
  • Several obvious very high correlations e.g. FTM and FTA
  • Interesting one that sticks out: DREB is highly correlated with PTS, FGM, 3PM, and 3PA. Is this simply that when there are many rebounds to be had there are more shots going up and thus more baskets made?
